<subSubSection id="079AB89BFF9BEE43FF060338825CFEA1" pageId="4" pageNumber="80" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="4F3FEB10FF9BEE43FF060338825CFEA1" blockId="4.[151,1436,151,428]" pageId="4" pageNumber="80">
<emphasis id="7DF43702FF9BEE43FF0603388163FED9" bold="true" box="[199,332,259,284]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="80" reason="1">Discussion.</emphasis>
The new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="88809093FF9BEE43FD60033F84E8FED9" authority="(Shi &amp; Zheng, 1998)" baseAuthorityName="Shi &amp; Zheng" baseAuthorityYear="1998" box="[673,1223,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Pseudocosmetura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anjiensis">
<emphasis id="7DF43702FF9BEE43FD60033F83FDFED9" box="[673,978,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="80">Pseudocosmetura anjiensis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="2B1196E1FF9BEE43FC23033F8490FED9" author="Shi, F. - M. &amp; Zheng, Z. - M." box="[994,1215,260,284]" pageId="4" pageNumber="80" pagination="54 - 57" refId="ref3414" refString="Shi, F. - M. &amp; Zheng, Z. - M. (1998) Orthoptera: Tettigonioidea. In: Uu H. (Ed.): Insects of Longwangshan Nature Reserve. China Forestry Publishing House, Beijing, pp. 54 - 57." type="book chapter" year="1998">Shi &amp; Zheng, 1998</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, but it differs from the latter: male cerci with basal area stout, apical area obviously thin, cylindrical, curved upwards; posterior margin of subgenital plate with a triangular notch.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="079AB89BFF9BEE43FF06034B817EFE69" pageId="4" pageNumber="80" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="4F3FEB10FF9BEE43FF06034B817EFE69" blockId="4.[151,1436,151,428]" pageId="4" pageNumber="80">
<emphasis id="7DF43702FF9BEE43FF06034B8161FE4D" bold="true" box="[199,334,368,392]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="80" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name of the new species is derived from Latin ‘ 
<emphasis id="7DF43702FF9BEE43FC65034A83FAFE4D" box="[932,981,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="80">curv</emphasis>
’, showing that male cercus is obviously curved upwards.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
